</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>SB519:v98#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="SB519"/><meta name="dc:title" content="SB &#xA;              519-&#xA;                AMENDED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Amended
               IN </span><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Senate
              </span> <span style="text-transform: uppercase">March 26, 2025</span><br/></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Senate Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 519</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Senator Archuleta<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 19, 2025</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> to add Article 8.3 (commencing with Section 999.90) to Chapter 6 of Division 4 of the Military and Veterans Code,</i></font> relating to veterans. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">SB 519, as amended, Archuleta.
                          Veterans.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the Department of Veterans Affairs. The department, among<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> other</i></font> services, provides veterans and their dependents and survivors with assistance in processing service-related disability claims, assistance in obtaining affordable housing, and information about health<font color="#B30000"><strike> ailments</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> issues</i></font> associated with military service.</div><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>This bill would declare the Legislature’s intent to enact legislation creating a task force that focuses on retaining veterans in California to help solve the shortage of labor and key professional skills, and improving the economic opportunities available to military families in the state.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would create the Veteran Task Force for the purpose of reversing the trend of veterans and individuals transitioning from the military who are leaving California to reside and work in another state. The bill would prescribe the composition of the task force, including, among others, the Secretary of Veterans Affairs. The bill would require the task force to, among other things, examine existing veterans benefits in California, assistance for individuals transitioning from the military, childcare availability, affordable housing, and other services and opportunities to retain veterans and their families in California.</div></i></font></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase"><font color="#B30000"><strike>NO</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>YES</i></font></span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.07331546777642284"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SECTION 1.</i></font></h3> <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Article 8.3 (commencing with Section 999.90) is added to Chapter 6 of Division 4 of the Military and Veterans Code, to read:</i></font></div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i></i></font><div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div><div id="id_32CED459-82DD-4E32-835D-7F1C9E1E37FB"><div><h5 style="text-align:left;">
                Article
               8.3. Veteran Task Force</h5></div></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">999.90.</h6> The Veteran Task Force is hereby created for the purpose of reversing the trend of veterans and individuals transitioning from the military who are leaving California to reside and work in another state.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">999.91.</h6> (a) The Veteran Task Force shall consist of all of the following members:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) The secretary, director, commissioner, chair, or adjutant general, as applicable, or their designee, from each of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Business, Consumer Services, and Housing Agency.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) California Health and Human Services Agency.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Department of Veterans Affairs.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Department of the California Highway Patrol.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Employment Development
						  Department.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(F) Governor’s Military Council.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(G) Governor’s Office of Business and Economic Development (Go-Biz).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(H) Military Department.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) The chairperson of the Assembly Appropriations Committee or a representative appointed by the Speaker of the Assembly.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) The chairperson of the Assembly Committee on Military and Veterans Affairs or a representative appointed by the Speaker of the Assembly.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) The chairperson of the Senate Appropriations Committee or a representative appointed by the Senate Committee on Rules.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) The chairperson of the Senate
						  Committee on Military and Veterans Affairs or a representative appointed by the Senate Committee on Rules.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) A representative of public or private institutions of higher education.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7) A representative of each of the following stakeholder organizations:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) CAL FIRE Local 2881.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) California Hispanic Chambers of Commerce.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) California Professional Firefighters.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) California State Sheriffs’ Association.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Chief Probation Officers of California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(F) International Brotherhood of
						  Teamsters.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(G) Peace Officers Research Association of California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(H) San Diego Military Advisory Council, who shall be the vice chairperson of the task force.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(I) Sheet Metal Air Rail Transportation Local Union 104.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(J) The State Building and Construction Trades Council of California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(K) U.S. VETS.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(L) VetFund Foundation, who shall be the chairperson of the task force.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(M) Veterans in Business Network.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Members of the task force shall not receive any
						  compensation.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">999.92.</h6> (a) The task force shall do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Examine various services, opportunities, and policies across departments that could be offered to veterans as incentives for them and their families to remain in California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Conceive, investigate, and recommend diverse ideas that would contribute to achieving the objective of retaining veterans in California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Examine all of the following objectives:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Existing veteran benefits in California.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Assistance for individuals
						  transitioning from the military.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) License portability for military and veteran spouses.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Childcare availability.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Affordable housing.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(F) Taxation relief.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(G) Veteran-owned businesses.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The task force may establish working groups, task forces, or other structures from within its membership or with outside members to assist it in its work.</div></p></div></div></i></font></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_AD1FFD5B-FC61-40AB-8250-A5B412AE992D"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>It is the intent of the Legislature to enact legislation creating a task force that focuses on retaining veterans in California to help solve the shortage of labor and key professional skills, and improving the economic opportunities available to military families in the state.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:BillSection></strike></font></div></div></body></html>
